I liked this recipe and followed it very closely, with the singular exception of adding in Italian mixed herbs in place of Herbs de Provence. I rubbed the herb/oil mixture under the skin of the chicken, as I do with all chickens that I roast. One thing to note: 400 degrees is quite high for roasting onions for more than an hour, so watch yours carefully. The tips of mine burned. In the future, I would add the onion a bit later in the cooking process. The fennel really lends a nice flavor. Also this seemed like a lot of oil, especially when you consider how much fat the chicken releases during cooking, so my vegetables were very drenched. I tossed the vegetables with some whole wheat pasta as a side dish and added some lemon to add in an acid note to brighten up the flavor, and then served this with a simple green salad. In the future, I'd up the amount of herbs, add the onions after 20 minutes of cooking, cut back a small amount in terms of the oil in the pan and add some garlic to the chicken cavity and squeeze some lemon over the finished chicken.

